Lesson Notes: iptables, Netfilter, PREROUTING

this lesson is for me so i can look at it later

Command i used

sudo iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -i lab0 -p tcp --syn -j REDIRECT --to-ports 9040


after looking deeper into command i learned more about kernel that Linux is using, more specific about Netfilter firewall

i realised the command is targeting Netfilter table (-t nat) called nat
and appended rule to the PREROUTING chain (which is one of the processing stages in the Linux packet flow)


flow

incoming packet
        ↓
PREROUTING
        ↓
routing decision
        ↓
INPUT or FORWARD
        ↓
POSTROUTING


PREROUTING happens before the kernel decides where to send the packet (that is why we intercept traffic here)

then we need to match packets arriving on interface lab0 (-i lab0)
and match only TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) packets (-p tcp)

when TCP starts clients send SYN (Synchronize flag) in handshake:

SYN
SYN-ACK
ACK


then jump to REDIRECT action where REDIRECT changes the packet destination to the local machine

in simple words, instead of going to the original destination server, the packet is redirected to a local service

then specify the local port where packets are redirected

--to-ports 9040


so again in simple terms it does following

original
z3r0 → google.com:443

with this rule
z3r0 → rootnode
        ↓
iptables PREROUTING
        ↓
redirect to localhost:9040
        ↓
Tor client
        ↓
Tor network
        ↓
destination


The client does not know the traffic was redirected.


why is PREROUTING required

Because the kernel must modify the packet before routing happens.

If we waited until later stages, the packet would already have been forwarded.

PREROUTING allows interception at the earliest stage.


revert rules

remove just this rule

sudo iptables -t nat -D PREROUTING -i lab0 -p tcp --syn -j REDIRECT --to-ports 9040

flush NAT (Network Address Translation) rules

sudo iptables -t nat -F
